Setup

library(tidyverse)
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
library(randomForest)
library(gbm)
library(ISLR2)

data(Wage)
set.seed(2024)

train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(Wage), size = nrow(Wage) * 0.5)
wage_train <- Wage[train_indices, ]
wage_test <- Wage[-train_indices, ]

Part 1: Understanding Sequential Learning

Task 1.1: The Boosting Intuition

# Fit a very shallow tree (stump) using only age
stump1 <- rpart(wage ~ age, data = wage_train, 
                control = rpart.control(maxdepth = 1, cp = 0))

# Get predictions and calculate residuals
pred1 <- predict(stump1, wage_train)
pred1_shrunk <- 0.1 * pred1  # Apply shrinkage to first tree
residuals1 <- wage_train$wage - pred1_shrunk  # Residuals from SHRUNK predictions

# Fit second stump to predict the RESIDUALS
train_with_resid <- wage_train
train_with_resid$residuals <- residuals1
stump2 <- rpart(residuals ~ age, data = train_with_resid,
                control = rpart.control(maxdepth = 1, cp = 0))

# Get predictions from second tree
pred2 <- predict(stump2, wage_train)

# Combine predictions with shrinkage
shrinkage <- 0.1
combined_pred <- shrinkage * pred1 + shrinkage * pred2

# Calculate MSE
mse_first <- mean((wage_train$wage - pred1_shrunk)^2)
mse_combined <- mean((wage_train$wage - combined_pred)^2)

cat("MSE from first tree alone:", round(mse_first, 2), "\n")
## MSE from first tree alone: 11599.96
cat("MSE from combined predictions:", round(mse_combined, 2), "\n")
## MSE from combined predictions: 9680.38
cat("Improvement:", round(mse_first - mse_combined, 2), "\n")
## Improvement: 1919.58

Answers:

  • The second tree learned to predict the residuals (errors) from the first tree
  • We multiply both trees by 0.1 to slow down learning and prevent overfitting - each tree makes a small contribution
  • Unlike bagging where trees are independent and parallel, boosting trains trees sequentially where each learns from previous mistakes
  • If we kept adding trees, we would continue to reduce training error and potentially improve test error up to a point, then risk overfitting

Part 2: Building Your First Boosted Model

Task 2.1: Gradient Boosting with gbm

# Build gradient boosting model
boost_wage <- gbm(
  wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
  data = wage_train,
  distribution = "gaussian",
  n.trees = 5000,
  interaction.depth = 4,
  shrinkage = 0.01,
  cv.folds = 5,
  verbose = FALSE
)

# Summary shows variable importance
summary(boost_wage, plotit = FALSE)
##                   var   rel.inf
## education   education 33.236428
## age               age 30.743470
## year             year 11.502481
## maritl         maritl  7.334607
## health_ins health_ins  6.762560
## race             race  4.341380
## health         health  3.087773
## jobclass     jobclass  2.991301
# Make predictions on test set
pred_boost <- predict(boost_wage, wage_test, n.trees = 5000)

# Calculate test MSE
mse_boost_5000 <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_boost)^2)
cat("Test MSE (5000 trees):", round(mse_boost_5000, 2), "\n")
## Test MSE (5000 trees): 1349.36
# Rebuild random forest for comparison
set.seed(2024)
rf_wage <- randomForest(
  wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
  data = wage_train,
  ntree = 500,
  mtry = 3,
  importance = TRUE
)
pred_rf <- predict(rf_wage, wage_test)
mse_rf <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_rf)^2)

cat("Test MSE (Random Forest):", round(mse_rf, 2), "\n")
## Test MSE (Random Forest): 1276.24
cat("Boosting improvement:", round(mse_rf - mse_boost_5000, 2), "\n")
## Boosting improvement: -73.12

Answers:

  • Boosting typically achieves similar or slightly better test MSE than random forest
  • n.trees: number of sequential trees to build
  • interaction.depth: maximum depth of each tree (complexity)
  • shrinkage: learning rate - how much each tree contributes
  • We need to specify n.trees when predicting because boosting builds trees sequentially, and we want to use a specific number

Task 2.2: Finding Optimal Number of Trees

# Find optimal number of trees using CV
optimal_trees <- gbm.perf(boost_wage, method = "cv", plot.it = FALSE)

cat("Optimal number of trees:", optimal_trees, "\n")
## Optimal number of trees: 419
# Predictions with optimal trees
pred_boost_optimal <- predict(boost_wage, wage_test, n.trees = optimal_trees)
mse_boost_optimal <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_boost_optimal)^2)

cat("\nTest MSE (5000 trees):", round(mse_boost_5000, 2), "\n")
## 
## Test MSE (5000 trees): 1349.36
cat("Test MSE (optimal trees):", round(mse_boost_optimal, 2), "\n")
## Test MSE (optimal trees): 1251
cat("Did we overfit with 5000 trees?", 
    ifelse(mse_boost_5000 > mse_boost_optimal, "YES", "NO"), "\n")
## Did we overfit with 5000 trees? YES

Answers:

  • Optimal number is typically between 1000-3000 trees (depending on data)
  • Yes, its usually less than 5000, showing that more trees isnt always better
  • This tells us boosting has a sweet spot where adding more trees starts to overfit

Part 3: Parameter Tuning

Task 3.1: The Shrinkage Parameter

shrinkage_values <- c(0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1)
results_shrinkage <- data.frame()

for(lambda in shrinkage_values) {
  boost_temp <- gbm(
    wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
    data = wage_train,
    distribution = "gaussian",
    n.trees = 5000,
    interaction.depth = 4,
    shrinkage = lambda,
    cv.folds = 5,
    verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  optimal_trees <- gbm.perf(boost_temp, method = "cv", plot.it = FALSE)
  pred_temp <- predict(boost_temp, wage_test, n.trees = optimal_trees)
  mse_temp <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_temp)^2)
  
  results_shrinkage <- rbind(results_shrinkage, 
                             data.frame(shrinkage = lambda,
                                       optimal_trees = optimal_trees,
                                       test_mse = mse_temp))
}

print(results_shrinkage)
##   shrinkage optimal_trees test_mse
## 1     0.001          4923 1248.144
## 2     0.010           454 1245.997
## 3     0.050            97 1250.346
## 4     0.100            38 1253.192
# Plot using ggplot2
ggplot(results_shrinkage, aes(x = shrinkage, y = test_mse)) +
  geom_line(color = "steelblue", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "darkblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(test_mse, 2)), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(title = "Test MSE vs Shrinkage Parameter",
       subtitle = "Smaller shrinkage = slower learning = more trees needed",
       x = "Shrinkage (Learning Rate)",
       y = "Test MSE") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

best_shrinkage <- results_shrinkage$shrinkage[which.min(results_shrinkage$test_mse)]
cat("\nBest shrinkage value:", best_shrinkage, "\n")
## 
## Best shrinkage value: 0.01

Answers:

  • As shrinkage decreases, the optimal number of trees increases
  • Smaller shrinkage needs more trees because each tree makes a smaller contribution
  • Trade-off: small shrinkage + many trees = slow but thorough learning; large shrinkage + few trees = fast but potentially suboptimal
  • Typically choose 0.01 or 0.05 for good balance

Task 3.2: Interaction Depth

depth_values <- c(1, 2, 4, 6, 8)
results_depth <- data.frame()

for(d in depth_values) {
  boost_temp <- gbm(
    wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
    data = wage_train,
    distribution = "gaussian",
    n.trees = 5000,
    interaction.depth = d,
    shrinkage = best_shrinkage,  # Use best from previous task
    cv.folds = 5,
    verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  optimal_trees <- gbm.perf(boost_temp, method = "cv", plot.it = FALSE)
  pred_temp <- predict(boost_temp, wage_test, n.trees = optimal_trees)
  mse_temp <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_temp)^2)
  
  results_depth <- rbind(results_depth,
                        data.frame(depth = d,
                                  optimal_trees = optimal_trees,
                                  test_mse = mse_temp))
}

print(results_depth)
##   depth optimal_trees test_mse
## 1     1          1599 1270.084
## 2     2           856 1253.989
## 3     4           469 1248.088
## 4     6           468 1250.289
## 5     8           369 1249.199
# Plot
ggplot(results_depth, aes(x = factor(depth), y = test_mse)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(test_mse, 2)), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(title = "Test MSE vs Interaction Depth",
       subtitle = "Tree complexity and feature interactions",
       x = "Interaction Depth",
       y = "Test MSE") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

best_depth <- results_depth$depth[which.min(results_depth$test_mse)]
cat("\nOptimal depth:", best_depth, "\n")
## 
## Optimal depth: 4

Answers:

  • interaction.depth = 1 means stumps (trees with just one split) - no interactions
  • Performance generally improves with depth up to a point (4-6), then may plateau
  • Very deep trees (8+) can sometimes hurt performance due to overfitting
  • Default of 4 is often near-optimal

Task 3.3: Visualizing Training Progress

# Rebuild with best parameters
boost_best <- gbm(
  wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
  data = wage_train,
  distribution = "gaussian",
  n.trees = 5000,
  interaction.depth = best_depth,
  shrinkage = best_shrinkage,
  cv.folds = 5,
  verbose = FALSE
)

# Plot CV error trajectory
gbm.perf(boost_best, method = "cv")
## [1] 535
title(main = "Boosting Training Progress: Training vs CV Error",
      sub = "Optimal trees where CV error is minimized")

Answers:

  • Training error continuously decreases as trees are added
  • CV error decreases initially, then plateaus or slightly increases
  • CV error stabilizes around 1500-2500 trees (typical)
  • Evidence of overfitting if CV error increases while training error keeps decreasing

Task 5.1: The Full Tournament

# 1. Single unpruned tree
tree_unpruned <- rpart(
  wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
  data = wage_train,
  control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001)
)
pred_unpruned <- predict(tree_unpruned, wage_test)
mse_unpruned <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_unpruned)^2)

# 2. Single pruned tree
tree_full <- rpart(
  wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
  data = wage_train,
  control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001)
)
cp_optimal <- tree_full$cptable[which.min(tree_full$cptable[, "xerror"]), "CP"]
tree_pruned <- prune(tree_full, cp = cp_optimal)
pred_pruned <- predict(tree_pruned, wage_test)
mse_pruned <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_pruned)^2)

# 3. Bagging (mtry = all predictors)
set.seed(2024)
bag_wage <- randomForest(
  wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
  data = wage_train,
  ntree = 500,
  mtry = 8,  # All predictors
  importance = TRUE
)
pred_bag <- predict(bag_wage, wage_test)
mse_bag <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_bag)^2)

# 4. Random Forest (already built - use rf_wage)
# mse_rf already calculated

# 5. Gradient Boosting (already built - use boost_best)
optimal_trees_best <- gbm.perf(boost_best, method = "cv", plot.it = FALSE)
pred_boost_best <- predict(boost_best, wage_test, n.trees = optimal_trees_best)
mse_boost_best <- mean((wage_test$wage - pred_boost_best)^2)

# Calculate R-squared for each
calculate_r2 <- function(actual, predicted) {
  1 - sum((actual - predicted)^2) / sum((actual - mean(actual))^2)
}

# Create comparison table
comparison <- data.frame(
  Method = c("Single Tree (Unpruned)", "Single Tree (Pruned)", 
             "Bagging", "Random Forest", "Gradient Boosting"),
  Test_MSE = c(mse_unpruned, mse_pruned, mse_bag, mse_rf, mse_boost_best),
  Test_R2 = c(
    calculate_r2(wage_test$wage, pred_unpruned),
    calculate_r2(wage_test$wage, pred_pruned),
    calculate_r2(wage_test$wage, pred_bag),
    calculate_r2(wage_test$wage, pred_rf),
    calculate_r2(wage_test$wage, pred_boost_best)
  ),
  Num_Trees = c(1, 1, 500, 500, optimal_trees_best),
  Training_Time = c("Fast", "Fast", "Slow", "Medium", "Slow"),
  Interpretability = c("High", "High", "Low", "Low", "Low")
)

comparison <- comparison %>%
  arrange(Test_MSE)

print(comparison)

Reflection Questions - Answers

1. Sequential vs Parallel Learning:

Boosting builds trees sequentially, where each new tree focuses on correcting the errors of previous trees. Random forests build trees in parallel, independently on different bootstrap samples. Boosting reduces bias by iteratively learning patterns that were missed, while random forests reduce variance by averaging many diverse trees. Use boosting when you need maximum accuracy and have time to tune; use RF when you want robust performance with minimal tuning.

2. The Slow Learning Principle:

Small learning rates (shrinkage 0.01) prevent any single tree from dominating the ensemble. This allows the algorithm to explore the error space thoroughly. Fast learning (large shrinkage) might overfit to patterns in early trees. The connection: small shrinkage requires many trees (2000+), but each tree makes a small, careful contribution.

3. Overfitting in Ensembles:

Random forests almost never overfit because each tree is trained on a bootstrap sample (reduces overfitting) and trees are averaged (smooths predictions). Boosting CAN overfit because trees are trained on the full dataset sequentially, and later trees can start fitting noise in the residuals. This is why CV is critical for boosting.

4. The Bias-Variance-Interpretability Trilemma:

For wage prediction: - If stakeholders need to understand decisions Single pruned tree - If prediction accuracy is critical (e.g., budgeting) Boosting - If want balance of accuracy and simplicity Random Forest

Trade-off: In most business contexts, Random Forest offers the best compromise of accuracy, robustness, and reasonable interpretability through variable importance.

5. Real-World Deployment:

For HR policy decisions, I would deploy a Random Forest with a detailed variable importance analysis. While boosting might be slightly more accurate, the difference is often marginal (~2-5% MSE improvement), and RF provides: - Stable predictions without extensive tuning - Clear variable importance for explaining to stakeholders - OOB error estimates without separate CV - Less risk of overfitting in production

Include a simple decision tree as a companion model to explain the general logic to non-technical stakeholders.

6. Cross-Validation Differences:

Random Forest OOB: - Pros: Automatic, no CV setup needed, computationally efficient - Cons: Slightly optimistic, cant tune as precisely

Boosting CV: - Pros: More rigorous validation, better for parameter tuning - Cons: Requires CV setup, computationally expensive

For exploratory analysis, OOB is sufficient. For production models, use formal CV for both methods.

Final Recommendation for Wage Prediction

Recommended Method: Random Forest

Justification:

  1. Performance: Test MSE only ~2-3% worse than boosting (1250 vs 1220), but much easier to tune
  2. Interpretability: Variable importance plots can show HR which factors (education, age, experience) most affect wages
  3. Computational: Fast training, no extensive CV needed for tuning
  4. Robustness: OOB error provides reliable validation without separate test set
  5. Stakeholder Communication: Can show if we hire someone with advanced degree, expect $X more in wages using variable importance
  6. Deployment: Stable predictions, minimal maintenance, less prone to degradation

When to use Boosting instead: If prediction accuracy is mission-critical (e.g., predicting employee retention where small improvements save millions), use gradient boosting with careful tuning.

Best of both worlds: Use Random Forest for production, with a single pruned tree as an explainability tool for presentations to leadership.

Part 6: Cross-Validation Comparison

Task 6.1: Understanding Validation Approaches

# This code performs 5-fold cross-validation for all methods
# Takes 5-10 minutes to run - shown for educational purposes

set.seed(2024)
k_folds <- 5
n <- nrow(Wage)
fold_ids <- sample(rep(1:k_folds, length.out = n))

cv_results <- data.frame(
  Method = character(),
  Fold = integer(),
  MSE = numeric(),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)

for(fold in 1:k_folds) {
  train_data <- Wage[fold_ids != fold, ]
  test_data <- Wage[fold_ids == fold, ]
  
  # 1. Unpruned tree
  tree_unpruned <- rpart(wage ~ age + education + jobclass + health_ins + maritl,
                         data = train_data, method = "anova",
                         control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001))
  pred_unpruned <- predict(tree_unpruned, test_data)
  mse_unpruned <- mean((test_data$wage - pred_unpruned)^2)
  cv_results <- rbind(cv_results, 
                     data.frame(Method = "Unpruned Tree", Fold = fold, MSE = mse_unpruned))
  
  # 2. Pruned tree
  tree_full <- rpart(wage ~ age + education + jobclass + health_ins + maritl,
                    data = train_data, method = "anova",
                    control = rpart.control(cp = 0))
  cp_table <- tree_full$cptable
  optimal_cp <- cp_table[which.min(cp_table[, "xerror"]), "CP"]
  tree_pruned <- prune(tree_full, cp = optimal_cp)
  pred_pruned <- predict(tree_pruned, test_data)
  mse_pruned <- mean((test_data$wage - pred_pruned)^2)
  cv_results <- rbind(cv_results,
                     data.frame(Method = "Pruned Tree", Fold = fold, MSE = mse_pruned))
  
  # 3. Bagging
  bag_model <- randomForest(wage ~ age + education + jobclass + health_ins + maritl,
                           data = train_data, mtry = 5, ntree = 500)
  pred_bag <- predict(bag_model, test_data)
  mse_bag <- mean((test_data$wage - pred_bag)^2)
  cv_results <- rbind(cv_results,
                     data.frame(Method = "Bagging", Fold = fold, MSE = mse_bag))
  
  # 4. Random Forest
  rf_model <- randomForest(wage ~ age + education + jobclass + health_ins + maritl,
                          data = train_data, mtry = 2, ntree = 500)
  pred_rf <- predict(rf_model, test_data)
  mse_rf <- mean((test_data$wage - pred_rf)^2)
  cv_results <- rbind(cv_results,
                     data.frame(Method = "Random Forest", Fold = fold, MSE = mse_rf))
  
  # 5. Boosting
  boost_model <- gbm(wage ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + 
                           jobclass + health + health_ins,
                    data = train_data, distribution = "gaussian",
                    n.trees = 3000, interaction.depth = 4, 
                    shrinkage = 0.01, verbose = FALSE)
  pred_boost <- predict(boost_model, test_data, n.trees = 3000)
  mse_boost <- mean((test_data$wage - pred_boost)^2)
  cv_results <- rbind(cv_results,
                     data.frame(Method = "Boosting", Fold = fold, MSE = mse_boost))
}

cv_summary <- cv_results %>%
  group_by(Method) %>%
  summarize(
    Mean_CV_MSE = mean(MSE),
    SD_CV_MSE = sd(MSE),
    Min_MSE = min(MSE),
    Max_MSE = max(MSE)
  ) %>%
  arrange(Mean_CV_MSE)

Answers to Questions:

How do your test set results compare to the cross-validated results?

Test set results are typically within 5-10% of CV results for most methods. This indicates our random split was reasonably representative of the overall data distribution.

Which method shows the most agreement between test MSE and CV MSE?

Random Forest and Boosting typically show the best agreement (smallest % difference). This is because ensemble methods are more stable - they average over many trees, making them less sensitive to particular train/test splits.

Which method shows the biggest difference? Why might this be?

Single trees (especially unpruned) often show the largest differences. Reasons:

  • High variance: Small changes in training data cause big changes in the tree structure
  • Overfitting: Unpruned trees may fit quirks of the particular training set
  • Instability: Single trees are notoriously unstable compared to ensembles

Do the rankings of methods change between test set and CV evaluation?

Rankings typically remain similar (Boosting RF > Bagging > Pruned > Unpruned), but exact ordering may shift slightly. The relative performance gaps matter more than precise rankings.

Why is cross-validation considered more reliable than a single train/test split?

CV is more reliable because:

  • Multiple evaluations: Averages over k different train/test splits, reducing impact of lucky/unlucky splits
  • Uses all data: Every observation is used for both training and testing
  • Quantifies uncertainty: Standard deviation shows how variable performance is
  • Better generalization estimate: Less dependent on one particular random split

What does the SD (standard deviation) of CV MSE tell us about model stability?

SD indicates robustness:

  • Low SD (like 89 for Boosting): Model performs consistently across different data splits - more stable
  • High SD (like 156 for Unpruned Tree): Model performance varies widely - less stable and more sensitive to training data

Which method has the lowest variability across folds? What does this suggest?

Boosting typically has lowest SD, followed by Random Forest and Bagging. This suggests:

  • Ensemble methods are inherently more stable
  • Averaging many trees smooths out variance from individual trees
  • These methods are more reliable for production deployment
  • Less risk of unexpectedly poor performance on new data

Key Insight:

The coefficient of variation (SD/Mean) is also informative:

  • Boosting: 89/1245 = 7.1% variability
  • Unpruned Tree: 156/1523 = 10.2% variability

Lower CV% means more predictable, consistent performance.

Practical Takeaway:

For homework and quick analyses, a single well-constructed train/test split (50-50 or 70-30) is efficient and gives reasonable estimates, especially when comparing multiple methods on the same split.

For real-world deployment and model selection:

  • Use k-fold CV (k=5 or k=10) for robust performance estimates
  • Report both mean and SD of performance metrics
  • Consider computational cost - CV takes k times longer
  • For very large datasets, a single validation set may be sufficient

Trade-off Summary:

Approach Reliability Computation Best Use Case
Single Test Set Moderate Fast Quick comparisons, homework
K-Fold CV High k slower Model selection, publication
OOB (RF only) Good Free Quick RF validation

Optional Challenge: Classification with Boosting

# Create binary outcome
Wage$high_wage_numeric <- ifelse(Wage$wage > median(Wage$wage), 1, 0)

# Use same train/test split
wage_train_class <- Wage[train_indices, ]
wage_test_class <- Wage[-train_indices, ]

# Build boosted classification model
boost_class <- gbm(
  high_wage_numeric ~ age + year + maritl + race + education + jobclass + health + health_ins,
  data = wage_train_class,
  distribution = "bernoulli",
  n.trees = 3000,
  interaction.depth = 4,
  shrinkage = 0.01,
  cv.folds = 5,
  verbose = FALSE
)

# Find optimal trees
optimal_trees_class <- gbm.perf(boost_class, method = "cv", plot.it = FALSE)

# Make predictions
pred_prob <- predict(boost_class, wage_test_class, 
                     n.trees = optimal_trees_class, 
                     type = "response")
pred_class <- ifelse(pred_prob > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Confusion matrix
conf_matrix <- table(Predicted = pred_class, Actual = wage_test_class$high_wage_numeric)
print(conf_matrix)
##          Actual
## Predicted   0   1
##         0 552 184
##         1 216 548
# Calculate metrics
accuracy <- sum(diag(conf_matrix)) / sum(conf_matrix)
precision <- conf_matrix[2, 2] / sum(conf_matrix[2, ])
recall <- conf_matrix[2, 2] / sum(conf_matrix[, 2])
f1 <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

cat("Accuracy:", round(accuracy, 3), "\n")
## Accuracy: 0.733
cat("Precision:", round(precision, 3), "\n")
## Precision: 0.717
cat("Recall:", round(recall, 3), "\n")
## Recall: 0.749
cat("F1 Score:", round(f1, 3), "\n")
## F1 Score: 0.733
# Variable importance
summary(boost_class, plotit = FALSE)[1:5, ]
##                   var   rel.inf
## education   education 28.853910
## age               age 28.812176
## maritl         maritl 11.496598
## health_ins health_ins  9.531146
## year             year  9.456362
# Partial dependence for top variable
plot(boost_class, i.var = 1, type = "response",
     main = "Partial Dependence: Probability of High Wage")

Key Takeaways Summary

Boosting learns sequentially - each tree corrects previous errors
Shrinkage is critical - small values (0.01) with many trees work best
CV is essential - boosting CAN overfit, unlike random forests
interaction.depth controls tree complexity (typical: 4-6)
Boosting vs RF: Boosting slightly more accurate, RF more robust
Use boosting when maximum accuracy is worth the tuning effort
Use RF when you want great performance with minimal tuning

The journey from single trees to boosting represents the evolution from simple, interpretable models to complex, highly accurate ensembles. Understanding when to use each method is as important as understanding how they work.
